<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong><em> Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.</em></p><h2 style=3D"font-weight=
: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;=
 letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bo=
ttom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px 5px;">GameStop</h2><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a Bloomberg article titled =E2=80=9C<a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24254000.278230/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMjMvYS1sb25ndGltZS1m=
aWRlbGl0eS1tYW5hZ2VyLXNvbGQtZ2FtZXN0b3AtYW5kLWhhcy1zb21lLXJlZ3JldHM/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cBaead28e6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">A Longtime Fidelity Manager Sold GameStop, and Has Some R=
egrets</a>.=E2=80=9D It begins like this:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">Joel Tillinghast has managed the Fidelity Low-Priced Stock Fund =
since it was created about 32 years ago, hunting for companies with shares =
that trade at bargain prices relative to their earnings potential. In 2020,=
 a suffering video-game retailer called GameStop Corp. fit that bill.</p></=
blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">No, look, I see where this is going=
, and I=E2=80=99m going to stop you right there. Sure, you bought GameStop =
below $10 per share in 2020, you sold it at like $49 in January, it closed =
yesterday at $219.34 and you have regrets. But ask yourself this: If you ow=
ned GameStop today, at $219.34 per share, up more than 1,000% year-to-date,=
 in the FIDELITY LOW-PRICED STOCK FUND, wouldn=E2=80=99t they have to fire =
you? Wouldn=E2=80=99t you spend all day every day smiling wanly at bosses a=
nd colleagues and interns and salespeople=C2=A0and family members and journ=
alists=C2=A0who keep coming up to you giggling and=C2=A0saying=C2=A0=E2=80=
=9Cso, how are those low-priced stocks doing these days? Got any good ones?=
=E2=80=9D Or: =E2=80=9CHey Joel, I forget, if a company is losing money but=
 trades at 200 times estimated 2023 earnings, is that cheap? That=E2=80=99s=
 cheap, right?=E2=80=9D Just a terrible life.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">No, you=C2=A0made the right decision. Sure you would have made more mone=
y for your clients if you had had diamond hands, but you are not running th=
e Fidelity Diamond Hands Fund, you=E2=80=99re running the Fidelity Low-Pric=
ed Stock Fund, and you=E2=80=99ve got to stick to your mandate.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That said, if I ran Fidelity I=E2=80=99d totally be ro=
lling out the Diamond Hands Fund. Give the people what they want!</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In Bloomberg Businessweek this week, <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24254000.278230/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMjMvc3RvY2stbWFya2V0LXJlZGRp=
dC1pbnZlc3RvcnMtaGF0ZS1zaG9ydC1zZWxsZXJzLWJ1dC1tYXJrZXQtbmVlZHMtdGhlbQ/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7bb1321b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;"> Brandon Kochkodin writes</a> about how meme-stock inv=
estors hate short sellers but they=C2=A0are an important part of the market=
 ecosystem:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Wall Street pros, o=
n the other hand, tend to regard shorts as a necessary part of the financia=
l landscape. They see financial markets not simply as a grocery store where=
 you can buy things you want, but as a kind of machine for discovering corr=
ect prices. Shorts add an input=E2=80=94without them, the only people with =
a reason to have an opinion about a company would be people interested in b=
uying or current owners thinking of getting out.</p></blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But I think that one counterintuitive lesson of the me=
me-stock thing is that=C2=A0<em>long=C2=A0</em>sellers are also an importan=
t part of the market ecosystem, and they have gone missing. A thing that of=
ten happens is that value investors think a stock is underpriced, so they b=
uy it, and then later a catalyst occurs and the stock goes up. And if it go=
es up really high, so that the value investors think it is overpriced, they=
 will sell it, which will prevent it from being too overpriced. In a liquid=
 market with daily prices, you get to make your investment decisions anew e=
ach day. If you bought a stock because it was underpriced and then it went =
up until it was overpriced, you sell it.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">I realize that I sound like an impossible simpleton, but this=C2=A0very=
 basic process ought to keep a lid on prices. Everyone who owns the stock h=
as some implicit reserve price, some maximum value for the stock; if the st=
ock goes above that value they will sell. The stock can=E2=80=99t go above=
=C2=A0<em>everyone=E2=80=99s </em>maximum=C2=A0value; at that point everyon=
e is a seller and no one is a buyer.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But wh=
at if it does? What if all the professional value investors buy at $10 and =
are like =E2=80=9CI think this is a $30 stock,=E2=80=9D and then it goes to=
 $60 and they=E2=80=99re like =E2=80=9Chuh guess I was a little too conserv=
ative, I will keep that quiet and congratulate myself on=C2=A0my foresight =
and huge profits=E2=80=9D and sell the stock, and then it goes to $400? Wha=
t if every research-based=C2=A0value-driven investor gets out, and other, u=
h, self-consciously non-value-driven investors keep driving up the price?=
=C2=A0<em>Who is left to sell?=C2=A0</em>The classic answer is =E2=80=9Csho=
rt sellers,=E2=80=9D but they all got blown up on the way from $10 to $200,=
 and have quite sensibly gotten out of this stock too.</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">In the first three days of this week, almost 17 million shares =
of GameStop worth about $3.5 billion have traded. That means people have so=
ld almost 17 million shares at prices mostly above $200 per share, somethin=
g like four times the price where Joel Tillinghast decided it was too rich =
for him and got out. Who were they? I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/24254000.278230/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGl=
uaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDcvc3BhY3MtY2FuLXNob290LW91dC1zcGFyY3M/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB3531f810" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;"> said the other day</a> that =E2=80=9Cthe list of top Ga=
meStop shareholders is a hilarious ghost town=E2=80=9D; virtually every<em>=
=C2=A0</em>professional value investor like Tillinghast seems to have dumpe=
d the stock during its wild January rally, and the top holders now are most=
ly a mix of index funds, insiders and options market makers. If you bought =
stock yesterday at $219, you didn=E2=80=99t buy it from some deep value inv=
estor who bought it at $5 and is finally now taking her profits. You bought=
 it from some other lunatic who paid $200 for it. (Or possibly <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24254000.278230/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMjIvZXZlcnl0aGluZy1zd=
GlsbC1taWdodC1iZS1zZWN1cml0aWVzLWZyYXVk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4e5f62b2" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> from the =
company</a>.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is, I think, part of why=
 the GameStop rally can last so long. There was some schedule of supply, so=
me set of reserve prices at which every fundamental-value-driven investor i=
n the stock would sell, and somehow the wild January Reddit-driven rally =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0when=C2=A0GameStop traded more than twice its market cap eve=
ry day for three straight days and kept doubling in price =E2=80=94=C2=A0<e=
m>lifted every one of those offers</em>.=C2=A0Everyone who was open to the=
=C2=A0<em>possibility=C2=A0</em>that GameStop might be overpriced, at any p=
rice whatsoever, sold. Everyone who=E2=80=99s left is either=C2=A0locked up=
 (insiders), utterly price-insensitive (index funds), looking for a good ti=
me and a gamble (Reddit, some hedge funds) or facilitating their gambling (=
options market makers). Once you blow through the maximum price on a stock,=
 there=E2=80=99s no reason for it to come back down.</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">I have said <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/24254000.278230/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGV=
zLzIwMjEtMDItMDEvZ2FtZXN0b3AtZ21lLWlzLW9sZC1uZXdzLWFmdGVyLXJlZGRpdC1kaXNjb3=
ZlcnMtc2lsdmVyLWZ1dHVyZXM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb30cc69d" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> things</a> like <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24254000.278230/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMTEvd2h5LWdhbWVz=
dG9wLWRpZG4tdC1zZWxsLWFueS1zdG9jay1kdXJpbmctdGhlLXJlZGRpdC1yYWxseQ/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cBb0442787" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;"> this</a> before, and I realize that it=C2=A0is exaggerate=
d and possibly insane. You could put=C2=A0it=C2=A0differently: Professional=
 value investors had a valuation cap at $60 or whatever, but a crowd of Red=
dit retail investors are smarter than they were and see=C2=A0value where th=
ey did not, fine. (Or: GameStop really is worth 10 times what it was worth =
in December, because of its new management team and the early progress on i=
ts new business plan, but traditional value investors are scared to get bac=
k in at a price that reflects that new value.) But I do think that the basi=
c, bizarre explanation for why GameStop=E2=80=99s stock price can stay so h=
igh and so volatile for so long is that there=E2=80=99s no one left to sell=
.</p><h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, =
Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border=
-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px=
 0px 5px;">Ancillary business</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Man <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24254000.278230/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMjQvY3JlZGl0LXN1aXNz=
ZS1zLW5ldy1jaGFpcm1hbi1zZW5kcy1jaGlsbC10aHJvdWdoLWludmVzdG1lbnQtYmFuaw/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb7be0197" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;"> that=E2=80=99s awkward</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Credit Suisse Group AG investment bankers expecting ne=
w Chairman Antonio Horta-Osorio to boost their spirits after an exodus of t=
op talent were left disappointed during a recent meeting in London.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The former Lloyds Banking Group Plc chief executiv=
e officer, in response to questions, told bankers who=E2=80=99d gathered in=
 person and virtually for the event that the firm had a great wealth manage=
ment business =E2=80=9Cwith ancillary services,=E2=80=9D according to sever=
al people who heard the remarks.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For some t=
op dealmakers and traders, those words were perceived as a blow, the people=
 said. The investment bank delivers more revenue than any other division at=
 the firm and ranks in the top 10 globally.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Horta-Osorio=E2=80=99s comment could mean more than just a few hurt egos. =
At the annual general meeting in April he=E2=80=99d already criticized the =
bank=E2=80=99s role in the Archegos Capital Management and Greensill scanda=
ls, pledging to take his time on a broad strategic review of the business. =
That=E2=80=99s put Credit Suisse bankers across the firm on high alert as t=
hey closely parse his words for clues about his plans for the firm -- and t=
heir own futures.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Not a great =
sign to find out that you=E2=80=99re in an =E2=80=9Cancillary service.=E2=
=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Once upon a time, the way investment=
 banks worked is that they were unlimited-liability partnerships and the se=
nior bankers were the partners. Everyone ran their own desks or divisions o=
r whatever, and they tried to bring in as much money as possible, and they =
were differentially rewarded for doing an especially good or bad job. But e=
veryone also knew that if one guy over in prime brokerage lost $5 billion, =
then they were all going to eat that loss together. It focused the mind a b=
it. Everyone knew that their partners=E2=80=99 fates were in their hands, a=
nd that their own fates were in their partners=E2=80=99 hands. It=E2=80=99s=
 not like you=E2=80=99d go snooping around in all of your partners=E2=80=99=
 businesses to see what they were up to, but =E2=80=A6 you would, a little?=
 If you had reason for concern? There would be risk committees to check up =
on everyone=E2=80=99s work, and those committees would take their jobs seri=
ously because their money was on the line. And the decision to promote some=
one to the partnership would be taken seriously; the partnership committee =
would ask not just =E2=80=9Cwill this person bring in a lot of money?=E2=80=
=9D but also =E2=80=9Cmight this person lose a lot of money?=E2=80=9D</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then of course if someone does lose $5 billi=
on, all the other partners chip in to pay it back, and while they are not=
=C2=A0<em>happy=C2=A0</em>about it they understand that at some level it is=
 their fault. =E2=80=9CWe should not have made that person a partner,=E2=80=
=9D they=E2=80=99ll think, or =E2=80=9Cwe should have kept a closer eye on =
that person=E2=80=99s business.=E2=80=9D The legal structure and culture ar=
guably lead=C2=A0to a sense of collective responsibility.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">Now investment banks are divisions inside of giant corporate=
 mega-banks, and as a formal legal matter a managing director in equity cap=
ital markets is not responsible for the debts of the prime brokerage divisi=
on. (Nor is a managing director in prime brokerage, for that matter.) On th=
e other hand if the prime brokerage division loses $5 billion, that=E2=80=
=99s going to eat into the bonuses of the people in leveraged finance. And =
if leveraged finance has a great year, and if most of the=C2=A0<em>other=C2=
=A0</em>banks manage=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>to lose $5 billion in their pri=
me brokerage divisions, then the leveraged finance bankers are going to fee=
l aggrieved. =E2=80=9CWe had a great year, our competitors at other banks a=
re getting paid well, and we=E2=80=99re not, just because some dope in prim=
e brokerage lost $5 billion? That=E2=80=99s not fair!=E2=80=9D And then the=
y leave:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While Horta-Osorio sur=
veys the options, dozens of key rainmakers have already voted with their fe=
et, departing for Wall Street rivals after the Archegos hit ravaged stock-b=
ased pay. Before the $5.5 billion loss, the investment bank had been resurg=
ent, profiting from advisory and trading opportunities. Now, Credit Suisse =
is already paring back its hedge fund unit and cutting ties with clients, p=
rompting speculation bigger changes are on the way.</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">More than 50 front office employees have left since the most recen=
t troubles began on March 1, as competitors view Switzerland=E2=80=99s seco=
nd-largest bank as fertile hunting ground for talent that otherwise would b=
e hard to poach. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0For many of the firm=E2=80=99s investment b=
ankers, the Archegos hit was particularly painful because it overshadowed o=
ne of the best periods for the business in years, driven by a trading boom,=
 leveraged finance deals and the surge in SPACs. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0With deal-m=
aking and trading conditions still favorable, other banks have swooped in t=
o scoop up talent.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yeah,=
 reasonable. Why should some investment banker be responsible for the losse=
s in prime brokerage?</p>
