om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Good tax trade</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24254000.278230/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucHJvcHV=
ibGljYS5vcmcvYXJ0aWNsZS9sb3JkLW9mLXRoZS1yb3Rocy1ob3ctdGVjaC1tb2d1bC1wZXRlci=
10aGllbC10dXJuZWQtYS1yZXRpcmVtZW50LWFjY291bnQtZm9yLXRoZS1taWRkbGUtY2xhc3Mta=
W50by1hLTUtYmlsbGlvbi1kb2xsYXItdGF4LWZyZWUtcGlnZ3ktYmFuaw/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cB7d3427b1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;">Here is an argument</a> that, if you are a young person who has jus=
t founded a potentially world-changing startup, instead of just giving your=
self shares in that startup for free, you should=C2=A0<em>buy=C2=A0</em>the=
m for a nominal price=C2=A0<em>inside a Roth IRA</em>. If you just give you=
rself the shares free and clear, and your startup does change the world and=
 the shares end up being worth billions of dollars, one day you will sell t=
hem and pay capital-gains taxes on your billions of dollars of gains.[1] On=
 the other hand, the way a Roth individual retirement account works under U=
.S. tax law is that you put money into it out of your after-tax earnings, a=
nd then when you are older you can withdraw the money =E2=80=94=C2=A0includ=
ing any gains =E2=80=94=C2=A0tax-free. So if you buy your founder=E2=80=99s=
 shares for $1,000 in a Roth IRA when you=E2=80=99re young, and then their =
value grows to, say, $5 billion, you can sell them after you turn 59 and a =
half and pay no taxes on the gains. Good trade!</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">It=E2=80=99s in ProPublica, which does not exactly=C2=A0<em>pitch </em=
>it as a good trade, but you can read between the lines. ProPublica asserts=
 that Peter Thiel used this approach with his PayPal founder=E2=80=99s shar=
es and now has $5 billion in his Roth IRA, so, you know, that=E2=80=99s an =
encouraging precedent. To be clear, though, this is not tax or legal advice=
, and there are arguments that it doesn=E2=80=99t actually work:</p><blockq=
uote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Thiel=E2=80=99s unusual stock purchase ri=
sked running afoul of rules designed to prevent IRAs from becoming illegal =
tax shelters. Investors aren=E2=80=99t allowed to buy assets for less than =
their true value through an IRA. The practice is sometimes known as =E2=80=
=9Cstuffing=E2=80=9D because it gets around the strict limits imposed by Co=
ngress on how much money can be put in a Roth.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">PayPal later disclosed details about the early history of the company i=
n an SEC filing before its initial public offering. The filing reveals that=
 Thiel=E2=80=99s founders=E2=80=99 shares were among those the company sold=
 to employees at =E2=80=9Cbelow fair value.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">Victor Fleischer, a tax law professor at the University of Califo=
rnia, Irvine who has written about the valuation of founders=E2=80=99 share=
s, read the PayPal filings at ProPublica=E2=80=99s request. Buying startup =
